On May 1, 2009, the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency closed Silverton Bank, N.A. and the FDIC was named as receiver. The loss on the investment is recorded on line RI- 5.k. "Net gains (losses) on sales of other assets". During the second quarter of 2009, the Bank increased its Allowance for Loan and Lease Losses through provisions of approximately $3.8 million due to additional impairments. Accordingly, gains or losses in one product type frequently offset gains or losses in other product types. For example, most of the firm's longer-term derivative contracts are sensitive to changes in interest rates and may be hedged with interest rate swaps. Similarly, a significant portion of the firm's cash and derivatives trading inventory has exposure to foreign currencies and may be hedged with foreign currency contracts. RI Memoranda 13a excludes losses on trading securities as all trading securities are recorded at fair value under the fair value option or other GAAP. RI Memoranda 13b excludes embedded derivative losses, which we would record under SFAS 133 without a SFAS 159 election.

In March 2007, the Bank received a one time allocation of $8.6 million in overhead.  Effective 4/1/07, the Bank has entered into an agreement with its parent which states that the parent agrees not to allocate any overhead to the Bank until its net income, after allocation, exceeds $2 million for a period of three years. Legg Mason Investment Counsel & Trust Company, NA ("Bank") now assesses and monitors its capital, capital needs and liquidity on a quarterly basis through its Investment Policy Committee. The Income & Expense sheet, Balance Sheet and Tier 1 Capital is reviewed monthly.  The Investment Policy Committee minutes are submitted to the Board of Directors.  In addition, as part of the quarterly financial review, the Bank's capital and liquidity will be reviewed by the Board.

2855914	54	15	53	174	CONF	0	0	0	65	507	0	0	0	0	0	0	0	600	0	0	0	true	65	0	0	149	10	94	346	93	0	0	35	82	119	62	0				Other real estate expenses	Impairment loss on Silverton Financial Services stock					Capital contribution				Year to date net loss for the bank is $1,795,000. In the first quarter we reported a loss of $1,262,000, driven by increased provision for loan and lease losses. In the second quarter we reported a loss of $533,000 which was largely due to an impairment loss of $507,000 on stock held in Silverton Financial Services, Inc., the bank holding company of Silverton Bank, National Association. Silverton Bank was the primary provider of correspondent banking services to the bank. On Friday, May 1, 2009, Silverton Bank was closed by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) was named Receiver. We do not expect to recover our original investment in the stock, and therefore have charged off the entire balance as of May 1, 2009. Excluding this non-recurring charge on Silverton stock, net loss for the second quarter would have been $26,000.

The implementation of this accounting principal requires the Bank to reclassify that portion of non-credit losses associated with investment securities, recorded through the income statement in 2008, out of beginning retained earnings on January 1, 2009 and into other comprehensive income.
